@page "/render-fragment-demo"

@*
    Verifies the Preview 5 release note for "Pass child content across render mode boundaries"
    (dotnet/aspnetcore #66754, backport of #66528). Before Preview 5 this combination threw
    InvalidOperationException because RenderFragment is a delegate and could not cross the
    SSR -> interactive boundary. Preview 5 prerenders the fragment, captures the render tree,
    and rehydrates it inside the interactive child.
*@

<PageTitle>RenderFragment across render mode boundaries</PageTitle>

<h1>RenderFragment across render mode boundaries</h1>

<p>
    The page itself renders SSR. The <code>InteractiveChild</code> below renders with
    <code>InteractiveServer</code> and receives <code>ChildContent</code> that was authored
    in the SSR parent. Clicking the "Bump" button should update the timestamp without
    re-rendering the SSR parent, proving the child is fully interactive even though it
    accepted SSR-authored child content.
</p>

<InteractiveChild @rendermode="InteractiveServer">
    <p id="ssr-projected">This paragraph was authored in the SSR parent and projected into the interactive child.</p>
    <p>Server time at SSR: <strong id="ssr-time">@DateTime.UtcNow.ToString("HH:mm:ss.fff")</strong></p>
</InteractiveChild>
